Missouri Earthquake Data Set

Christopher Prener, Ph.D.

January 13, 2017

Introduction

This notebook details the creation of a data set of earthquakes in Missouri.

Project Set Up

Since our notebook resides in a subdirectory of the R project called doc, all relative paths to folders as in the import("data/earthquakes.csv") are assumed to subdirectories of doc. This, of course, is not the case. Rather, we want our notebook to assume that relatve paths of the folder with the R project file in it. We can use

knitr::opts_knit$set(root.dir = here::here())

This is a critically important step. It allows us to continue using relative paths and a logical, sustainable file system. Moreover, we can do this while also not using the setwd() function, which would be used to hard code a file path like setwd("/Users/jsmith/Documents/SOC5650/MOEarthquakes"). The here() function finds a projects root directory, and can be used to direct knitr appropriately. The beauty of this arrangement is that this file can be executed on any computer, since here() will always resolve to the appropriate project directory for MOEarthquakes. Doing so increases the reproducibility of our work.

Dependencies

The following packages are required for this notebook:

library(dplyr)        # data wrangling
library(ggplot2)      # plotting
library(rio)          # data import
library(sf)           # spatial data tool
library(tigris)       # download census shapefiles

Obtaining Raw Data

The data were obtained from the USGS Earthquake Catalog. The search parameters used were for earthquakes of at least a magnitude of 2.0 between 1973-01-01 00:00:00 and 2017-12-31 23:59:59. A custom rectanlge around Missouri was drawn that covered the following coordinates - [35.909, 40.699] Latitude and [-95.845, -88.989] Longitude. These were output as CSV data and ordered with the oldest event first. They were saved to the file earthquakes.csv available in this repository.

quakes <- import("data/earthquakes.csv")

Cleaning the Earthquake Data

Our first task is the clean the earthquake data. The USGS Earthquake Catalog does not allow for searching by political geographies but rather requires us to download all earthquakes that occur in a rectangular area. Given Missouris shape, this means we have downloaded a number of earthquakes that occured in surrounding states. We want to remove those from our data set, and will do so using a technique called a spatial join.

Obtaining Spatial Data

Well start by downloading geometric data for all states using the tigris package, and then convert it to a simple feature object. Simple feature objects are an effecient and easy way to work with spatial data in r. However, they are relatively new and older packages like tigirs do not use simple features by default. What we really need is just the Missouri state boundary, so well extract that from the larger data set after we download and convert the data.

# download us states data
us <- states(year = 2015)
# convert to simple feature
us <- st_as_sf(us)
# extract missouri data
mo <- filter(us, GEOID == "29")
# remove states data
rm(us)

We can check that the conversion worked by making a simple map of Missouri using the geom_sf() geom from ggplot2. This geom is currently only available from the development version, which needs to be downloaded and installed from GitHub.

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = mo)

Adding Earthquakes to Map

For the next map, well add the earthqukes. The quakes data frame includes variables measuring longitude and latitutde, which can be used to project the data on the map.

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = mo) +
  geom_point(data = quakes, mapping = aes(x=longitude, y=latitude))

This map gives a clear sense of our data cleaning task - there are a considerable number of points that fall outside the state boundary that we are not interested in for this exercise.

Converting quakes to a Simple Features

Before we convert our quakes data frame (which is a tabular object that contains geometric data) into a geometric object, we need to make a decision about the coordinate system we will use for our data. Since they are already in decimal degrees, and since data from tigris uses the NAD1983 standard, well use NAD1983 as well.

The sf package includes a tool for confirming which coordinate system is being used by a geometric object:

st_crs(mo)
Coordinate Reference System:
  EPSG: 4269 
  proj4string: "+proj=longlat +ellps=GRS80 +towgs84=0,0,0,0,0,0,0 +no_defs"

The EPSG value refers to the identification number of the coordinate system in the EPSG data base. EPSG stands for European Petroleum Survey Group. The value 4269 is the EPSG identification number for NAD1983.

With a coordinate system selected, we can convert our object to a geometric one:

quakesGeo <- st_as_sf(quakes, coords = c("longitude", "latitude"), crs = 4269)

To check that it converted correctly, we can make a map with it. Notice how the ggplot() syntax is simpler with a simple feature object than it is when we are trying to map a data frame.

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = mo) +
  geom_sf(data = quakesGeo)

Our map looks like the previous one!

Spatial Joins

Our goal with the spatial join is to select only the points on the map that fall within Missouri. We can use the st_join() function to accomplish this. The ordering is important here - quakesGeo, our point data, should be listed first.

This will produce a geometric object that contains state information applied to each point. If the earthquake is within Missouri, it will have the data from the state geometric data. If it is outside of Missouri, it will have NA for the state data columns. We can use dplyrs filter() function to extract only the points within Missouri.

This code arrangement is called a pipeline. Each time you see the %>% operator, think of the word then. We can read the pipeline like so:

  1. Take the quakesGeo data and then
  2. Combine it with the mo data using a spatial join, then
  3. Extract all of the observations that are within Missouri and
  4. Assign the results to a new geometric object named quakesMO

The period in st_join() is a placeholder, instructing st_join() to reference quakesGeo at the point in the function where the period appears.

quakesGeo  %>%
  st_join(., mo) %>%
  filter(STUSPS == "MO") -> quakesMO
although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_intersects assumes that they are planar

We can check our work again by mapping the newly joined data:

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = mo) +
  geom_sf(data = quakesMO)

The st_join() function will append all of the variables from mo to our data as well, so well want to clean up the data frame a bit before moving on.

To keep things simple for this example, well only retain the time, depth, mag, and place variables:

quakesMO <- select(quakesMO, time, depth, mag, place)

Writing the Results to a Shapefile

Before we continue, well write the results of our geoprocessing to a shapefile so we can use the data later without re-creating it. This will also allow us to open the shapefile in a program like ArcGIS if we wanted to produce a more finished looking map. Well want to create a folder in the results subdirectory to store these files:

dir.create("results/GEO_Earthquakes")

With the folder made, we can save the shapefile:

st_write(quakesMO, "results/GEO_Earthquakes/GEO_Earthquakes.shp")
Writing layer `GEO_Earthquakes' to data source `results/GEO_Earthquakes/GEO_Earthquakes.shp' using driver `ESRI Shapefile'
features:       989
fields:         4
geometry type:  Point

Well also write these data as a .geojson file so that they can be previewed on GitHub. GeoJSON files are plain-text versions of shapefiles.

st_write(quakesMO, "results/GEO_Earthquakes/GEO_Earthquakes.geojson")
